# CRUD Examples

Three beginner-friendly Node.js apps showing how to do **Create, Read, Update, and Delete** (CRUD) operations with three different databases — **MongoDB**, **MySQL**, and **SQLite**.

Each app has its own folder, its own server, and its own frontend page. They all look and work the same way, but use a different database under the hood.

---

## What is CRUD?

CRUD stands for the four basic things you can do with data:

| Letter | Action | Example |
|--------|--------|---------|
| **C** | Create | Add a new item |
| **R** | Read | Show all items |
| **U** | Update | Edit an item |
| **D** | Delete | Remove an item |

---

## Project Structure

```
crud_examples/
├── mongodb_crud/        # App using MongoDB  → runs on port 3000
│   ├── server.js
│   ├── package.json
│   └── public/
│       └── index.html
│
├── mysql_crud/          # App using MySQL    → runs on port 3001
│   ├── server.js
│   ├── package.json
│   └── public/
│       └── index.html
│
└── sqlite_crud/         # App using SQLite   → runs on port 3002
    ├── server.js
    ├── package.json
    └── public/
        └── index.html
```

---

## Requirements

Make sure you have these installed before you start:

- [Node.js](https://nodejs.org) (v16 or higher)
- [npm](https://www.npmjs.com) (comes with Node.js)
- **For MongoDB:** [MongoDB Community Server](https://www.mongodb.com/try/download/community) running locally
- **For MySQL:** [MySQL Server](https://dev.mysql.com/downloads/mysql/) running locally
- **For SQLite:** Nothing extra — SQLite is a file-based database, it's built in

---

## Setup & Running Each App

### MongoDB CRUD

**1. Start MongoDB** on your machine (default port 27017).

**2. Install dependencies and start the server:**
```bash
cd mongodb_crud
npm install
npm start
```

**3. Open your browser:** [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000)

---

### MySQL CRUD

**1. Start MySQL** on your machine and create a database and table:
```sql
CREATE DATABASE crud_db;
USE crud_db;
CREATE TABLE items (
  id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
  name VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
  description TEXT
);
```

**2. Update the database credentials** in `mysql_crud/server.js`:
```js
const db = mysql.createConnection({
  host: 'localhost',
  user: 'your_username',      // change this
  password: 'your_password',  // change this
  database: 'crud_db'
});
```

**3. Install dependencies and start the server:**
```bash
cd mysql_crud
npm install
npm start
```

**4. Open your browser:** [http://localhost:3001](http://localhost:3001)

---

### SQLite CRUD

SQLite doesn't need any setup — it creates a database file automatically.

**1. Install dependencies and start the server:**
```bash
cd sqlite_crud
npm install
npm start
```

**2. Open your browser:** [http://localhost:3002](http://localhost:3002)

---

## How the Frontend Works

Each app has a single HTML page that lets you:

- **Add** a new item by filling in the Name and Description fields and clicking **+ Add Item**
- **Edit** an existing item by clicking the **Edit** button — this fills the form with the current values so you can change them
- **Delete** an item by clicking the **Delete** button — it will ask you to confirm first
- **Cancel** an edit by clicking **Cancel** to clear the form

The page talks to the server in the background (using `fetch`) so it never needs to reload.

---

## API Endpoints

Each server exposes the same REST API (just on a different port):

| Method | URL | What it does |
|--------|-----|-------------|
| `GET` | `/api/items` | Get all items |
| `POST` | `/api/items` | Add a new item |
| `PUT` | `/api/items/:id` | Update an item by ID |
| `DELETE` | `/api/items/:id` | Delete an item by ID |

**Example — Add a new item:**
```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/items \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"name": "Apple", "description": "A red fruit"}'
```

---

## Dependencies

| Package | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `express` | Web server framework — handles routes and requests |
| `body-parser` | Reads JSON data sent from the frontend |
| `cors` | Allows the frontend to talk to the server from the browser |
| `mongoose` | *(MongoDB only)* Makes it easy to work with MongoDB |
| `mysql2` | *(MySQL only)* Connects Node.js to a MySQL database |
| `sqlite3` | *(SQLite only)* Connects Node.js to a SQLite database file |

---

## Database Comparison

| Feature | MongoDB | MySQL | SQLite |
|---------|---------|-------|--------|
| Type | NoSQL (documents) | SQL (tables) | SQL (tables) |
| Setup needed | Yes (install + run) | Yes (install + run) | No — file only |
| Good for | Flexible data, fast prototyping | Structured data, production apps | Small apps, learning, local use |
| ID field | `_id` (auto) | `id` (auto-increment) | `id` (auto-increment) |

---

## UI Design

The redesigned interface uses a **dark theme** with each app color-coded:

- 🟢 **MongoDB** — Green accent
- 🟠 **MySQL** — Orange accent  
- 🟣 **SQLite** — Purple accent

All three share the same layout: a form card at the top for adding/editing, and a live item list below with an item counter badge.

---

## Troubleshooting

**"Cannot connect to server" error on the page**
→ Make sure you ran `npm start` in the correct folder and that the required database service is running.

**MySQL "Access denied" error**
→ Double-check the username and password in `server.js`.

**Port already in use**
→ Change the `PORT` variable at the top of `server.js` to a free port, and update the `API_URL` in `public/index.html` to match.

**`npm install` fails**
→ Make sure Node.js v16+ is installed. Run `node -v` to check.
